'''Anthony Ward Clare''' (24 December 1942 &ndash; 28 October 2007) was an Irish [[psychiatrist]] well known in the UK and Ireland as a presenter of radio and TV programmes.

==Career==
Clare was born in [[Dublin]], in the [[Republic of Ireland]] and educated at [[Gonzaga College]]. In 1966, he graduated from [[University College, Dublin]] (UCD) where he was an auditor of the [[Literary and Historical Society (University College Dublin)|Literary and Historical Society]]. During his time in UCD, he won the 1964 [[John Smith Memorial Mace|Observer Mace]] debating competition, speaking in a team with [[Patrick Cosgrave]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article2773500.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Anthony Clare | date=31 October 2007 | accessdate=30 March 2010}}</ref> Following initial training in psychiatry at [[St Patrick's Hospital]], Dublin, he moved to the Institute of Psychiatry at The [[Maudsley Hospital]], in London where he studied under Professor [[Michael Shepherd (psychiatrist)|Michael Shepherd]]. Clare held a doctorate in medicine and a master's degree in philosophy, and was a fellow of the [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]].<ref>''The Irish Times'', "Prof. Anthony Clare dies unexpectedly in Paris", October 30th, 2007</ref>

Author of several popular books on psychiatry, Clare held the positions of Professor of Clinical Psychiatry at [[Trinity College, Dublin]] and Medical Director of [[St. Patrick's Hospital]], Dublin. He was due to retire from his current post as Consultant General Adult Psychiatrist at St. Edmundsbury Hospital in [[Lucan, County Dublin]] when he died suddenly of a heart attack in [[Paris]] at the age of 64.<ref>{{cite news
|url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUKL3059702520071030
|publisher = [[Reuters]]
|title = Psychiatrist and broadcaster Anthony Clare dies
|accessdate = 1 November 2007
| date=30 October 2007}}</ref> 

In the 1980s and 1990s, Clare was the best-known psychiatrist in Britain. His first media appearances were on the light-hearted [[BBC Radio 4]] current affairs programme ''Stop the Week''. He was also for many years the voice of the BBC popular science programme ''[[Q.E.D. (BBC TV series)|QED]]''. Clare became famous for his probing interviews on radio and television with well-known figures such as [[Bob Monkhouse]] and [[Paddy Ashdown]]<ref name="BBC news 24">{{cite news
|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/7068743.stm 
|publisher = BBC News 24
|title = Psychiatrist Anthony Clare dies
|accessdate = 30 October 2007
 | date=30 October 2007| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20071031193545/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/7068743.stm| archivedate= 31 October 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> in several series of ''In the Psychiatrist's Chair'',<ref>{{cite web
|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/historyofthebbc/resources/factsheets/1980s.pdf
|accessdate = 30 October 2007|title = History of the BBC: 1980s
|publisher = [[BBC]]
}}</ref> which ran from 1982.<ref>[http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-anthony-clare-395574.html ''Independent'' obituary]</ref> 

As a young man Clare lost his [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] faith and later explained why in a newspaper interview.   
<blockquote>''I can't really believe in a God that can suddenly and haphazardly intervene during one moment of history, causing air crashes, genocide and famine.''<ref name="BBC news 24"/></blockquote>    
  
Clare married Jane Hogan in 1966 and they had seven children together.<ref name="BBC news 24"/>

